  "description": "Col Conrad has a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) and Masters in Defence Studies from the Royal Military College, Kingston, Ontario.  He was commissioned as a Naval Officer (MARS) in May, 1987. After retraining as an army combat logistics officer he has served in virtually every command billet possible in 1 Service Battalion in Western Canada from platoon commander to Commanding Officer in 2005-2006.  Over half of his career has been spent with the Army of the West in 1 Canadian [&#8230;]",
  "content:encoded": "<p>Col Conrad has a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) and Masters in Defence Studies from the <a title=\"Royal Military College\" href=\"http://www.rmc.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Royal Military College</a>, <a title=\"City of Kingston\" href=\"https://www.cityofkingston.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Kingston</a>, <a title=\"Ontario\" href=\"http://www.ontario.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Ontario</a>.  He was commissioned as a <a title=\"Royal Canadian Navy\" href=\"http://www.navy-marine.forces.gc.ca/en/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">Naval</a> Officer (MARS) in May, 1987.</p>\n<p>After retraining as an army combat <a title=\"Logistics Branch\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/caf-community-branches-logistics/about-us.page\" target=\"_blank\">logistics</a> officer he has served in virtually every command billet possible in <a title=\"1 Service Battalion\" href=\"http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/1-service-battalion/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">1 Service Battalion</a> in Western Canada from platoon commander to Commanding Officer in 2005-2006.  Over half of his career has been spent with the Army of the West in <a title=\"1 Canadian Mechanized Brigade Group\" href=\"http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/1-cmbg/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">1 Canadian Mechanized Brigade Group</a>.  Subsequent postings have included a year on Atlantic Area Staff (now the <a title=\"5th Canadian Division\" href=\"http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/atlantic/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">5th Canadian Division</a>) in <a title=\"City of Halifax\" href=\"http://www.halifax.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Halifax</a>, a year at the <a title=\"Canadian Army Doctrine and Training Centre\" href=\"http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/doctrine-training/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Army Doctrine and Training Centre</a> in Kingston as well as the G4 (Principle Staff officer for Logistics) for HQ Land Forces Central Area (now the <a title=\"4th Canadian Division\" href=\"http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/central/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">4th Canadian Division</a>) in <a title=\"City of Toronto\" href=\"http://toronto.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Toronto</a>.</p>\n<p>He has served in late 2006 to May 2007 as an instructor at the <a title=\"Canadian Forces Command and Staff College\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/training-establishments/command-staffcollege-index.page\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Forces Command and Staff College</a> and most recently finished up a two-year tour serving as a Deputy Director and Instructor at the <a title=\"Canadian Forces College\" href=\"http://www.cfc.forces.gc.ca/221-eng.html\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Forces College</a> in Toronto.</p>\n<p>Col Conrad has previous operational experience in Cambodia (March to November, 1993) with <a title=\"United Nations Transitional Authority in Cambodia\" href=\"http://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/missions/past/untac.htm\" target=\"_blank\">UNTAC</a> and North West Bosnia (March to September 2000) with NATO’s Stabilization Force (<a title=\"SFOR\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-past/op-palladium.page\" target=\"_blank\">SFOR</a>). He has completed a tour as the Commanding Officer of the National Support Element, the logistics battalion responsible for sustaining the Canadian Task Force in Southern Afghanistan from February to August 2006 (<a title=\"Operation Archer\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-past/op-archer.page\" target=\"_blank\">Operation Archer</a>/<a title=\"US Operation Enduring Freedom\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Enduring_Freedom\" target=\"_blank\">US Operation Enduring Freedom</a>).</p>\n<p>Col Conrad was decorated with the <a title=\"Meritorious Service Medal\" href=\"http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhr-ddhr/chc-tdh/chart-tableau-eng.asp?ref=MSM\" target=\"_blank\">Meritorious Service Medal</a> for his leadership in Kandahar on this difficult tour.  Colonel Conrad currently commands <a title=\"41 Canadian Brigade Group\" href=\"http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/41-cbg/index.page\" target=\"_blank\">41 Canadian Brigade Group</a> in the army reserve and works full time as a senior manager with the <a title=\"Alberta Environment and Sustainable Resources Development\" href=\"http://esrd.alberta.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Alberta Environment and Sustainable Resources Development</a>.  A published freelance author, his first book, <em>What the Thunder Said</em>, was selected by the Book of the Month Club and was nominated for the 2009 <a title=\"Canadian Writers Trust Award\" href=\"http://www.writerstrust.com/awards.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Writers Trust Award</a> in the Non Fiction category.</p>\n<p>He is married to Martha Rutherford Conrad and has four children Aidan, Morgan, Harriet and Grace.</p>\n<p>You can purchase Col Conrad&#8217;s book through my <a title=\"Amazon.ca\" href=\"http://www.amazon.ca?_encoding=UTF8&tag=thecanamilihi-20\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon</a> link.</p>\n<p>Follow me on Twitter @MikeLacroix32</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">You can support this site by shopping on <a title=\"Amazon.ca\" href=\"http://www.amazon.ca?_encoding=UTF8&tag=thecanamilihi-20\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon</a>.  You still enjoy Amazon&#8217;s great prices, but a portion of your purchase goes to supporting the show.</p>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-812-22\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/CMHP-Episode-037-Col-John-Conrad.mp3?_=22\" /><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/CMHP-Episode-037-Col-John-Conrad.mp3\">http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/CMHP-Episode-037-Col-John-Conrad.mp3</a></audio>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\"> <a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/10429838_542309062546393_543450047915798222_n.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-819\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/10429838_542309062546393_543450047915798222_n-249x300.jpg\" alt=\"10429838_542309062546393_543450047915798222_n\" width=\"249\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/10429838_542309062546393_543450047915798222_n-249x300.jpg 249w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/10429838_542309062546393_543450047915798222_n.jpg 507w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 249px) 100vw, 249px\" /></a></p>\n<p>November 1984, Royal Military College, Kingston. Getting crushed by West Point in Rugby as a member of Royal Roads RFC.</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\"><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/323446_121686127942024_1698107772_o.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-815\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/323446_121686127942024_1698107772_o-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"323446_121686127942024_1698107772_o\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/323446_121686127942024_1698107772_o-300x225.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/323446_121686127942024_1698107772_o-1024x768.jpg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/323446_121686127942024_1698107772_o.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>A vital supply convoy in the Sha Wali Kot District, Northern Kandahar Province in 2006</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\"><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/291089_121686867941950_2134422804_o.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-814\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/291089_121686867941950_2134422804_o-300x208.jpg\" alt=\"291089_121686867941950_2134422804_o\" width=\"300\" height=\"208\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/291089_121686867941950_2134422804_o-300x208.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/291089_121686867941950_2134422804_o-1024x712.jpg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/291089_121686867941950_2134422804_o.jpg 1238w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Forward Operating Base Martello. Lunch with Captain Chris Wood.</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\"><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/326423_121688847941752_1462817889_o.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-816\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/326423_121688847941752_1462817889_o-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"326423_121688847941752_1462817889_o\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/326423_121688847941752_1462817889_o-300x198.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/326423_121688847941752_1462817889_o-1024x678.jpg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/326423_121688847941752_1462817889_o.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">Signing for the battalion on the Kandahar Airfield March 2006.</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">  <a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/doucet-1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-820\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/doucet-1-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"doucet-1\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/doucet-1-200x300.jpg 200w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/doucet-1.jpg 250w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px\" /></a> <a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/332771_101126549997982_1021589236_o.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-817\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/332771_101126549997982_1021589236_o-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"332771_101126549997982_1021589236_o\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/332771_101126549997982_1021589236_o-200x300.jpg 200w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/332771_101126549997982_1021589236_o.jpg 640w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px\" /></a><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/John-Conrad.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-813\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/John-Conrad.jpg\" alt=\"John%20Conrad\" width=\"199\" height=\"298\" /></a></p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">John Conrad is an author with more than 28 years experience in the Canadian Forces and has published &#8220;What The Thunder Said&#8221; and &#8220;Scarce Heard Amid The Guns Below&#8221;.</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\"><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1799886_542306612546638_2173256321297563355_o.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-818\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1799886_542306612546638_2173256321297563355_o-300x223.jpg\" alt=\"1799886_542306612546638_2173256321297563355_o\" width=\"300\" height=\"223\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1799886_542306612546638_2173256321297563355_o-300x223.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1799886_542306612546638_2173256321297563355_o-1024x764.jpg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1799886_542306612546638_2173256321297563355_o.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">Col Conrad poses in front of a Universal Carrier, also known as a Bren Gun Carrier.</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\"><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/image.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-821\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/image-300x168.jpg\" alt=\"image\" width=\"300\" height=\"168\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/image-300x168.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/image.jpg 620w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">Col Conrad assumes command of 41 Canadian Brigade Group on September 7, 2013</p>\n",
